with authorization2star  aZimbabwe’s crisis since 2000 has produced a dramatic global scattering of people. This volume investigates this enforced dispersal, and the processes shaping the emergence of a new "diaspora" of Zimbabweans abroad, focusing on the most important concentrations in South Africa and in Britain. Not only is this the first book on the diasporic connections created through Zimbabwe’s multifaceted crisis, but it also offers an innovative combination of research on the political, economic, cultural and legal dimensions of movement across borders and survival thereafter with a discussion of shifting identities and cultural change. It highlights the ways in which new movements are connected to older flows, and how displacements across physical borders are intimately linked to the reworking of conceptual borders in both sending and receiving states. The book is essential reading for researchers/students in migration, diaspora and postcolonial literary studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aForced migrationzZimbabwe. 0aZimbabweanszForeign countriesxPolitics and government. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aChikwava, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChinouya, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKriger, Norma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMano, Winston, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMbiba, Beacon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGregor, JoAnn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGregor, JoAnn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMuzondidya, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPasura